{
  "doc_id": "42774",
  "text": "In the present study, the levels of MDA and carbonyl contents in the plasma and 8-OhdG concentration in the urine were determined to evaluate the oxidative damage to DNA, lipids, and proteins in H1N1 infected patients and the non-infected control subjects. 8-OhdG is one of the predominant forms of free radical-induced lesions of DNA and is excreted into the urine. The urinary 8-OhdG is considered as an important biomarker of generalized and cellular oxidative stress to DNA [CITATION_1] . In this study, the level of urinary 8-OhdG was significantly higher in H1N1 infected patients than in the control subjects. It has been reported that DNA damage is induced in human leucocytes infected by the influenza virus, and the DNA damage due to influenza virus infection is believed to be related to apoptosis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Lipid peroxidation and protein oxidation were also increased in the plasma of H1N1 infected patients. Recently, lipid peroxidation and protein oxidation have become the subject of interest and they have been performed as biomarkers of oxidative damage in human studies [CITATION_4] . Specifically, the finding of an enhanced lipid peroxidation level in the plasma of H1N1 infected patients is similar to that in the other studies, providing evidence for the presence of oxidative stress during influenza virus infection [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
